{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:01:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:01:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16820"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16820"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.87,0.04,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67106"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9511"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52561"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3089"},{"type":"tags","id":"3241"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5644"},{"type":"tags","id":"7903"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67106"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of a rash. He has a history of histrionic personality disorder but no other significant medical conditions and takes no regular medications. During the consultation, he makes prolonged eye contact, touches your arm frequently, and makes suggestive comments about your appearance. He has attended the practice three times in the past month with minor complaints, always requesting to see you specifically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He moves unnecessarily close to you during the examination and continues to make flirtatious remarks despite your professional demeanour. The rash appears to be a mild contact dermatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ignore the behaviour and continue the consultation","Directly address the inappropriate behaviour and establish clear boundaries","Immediately terminate the consultation","Transfer care to another clinician without discussion","Schedule more frequent follow-up appointments"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a challenging situation involving a patient with histrionic personality disorder displaying inappropriate seductive behaviour. People with histrionic personality disorder often exhibit attention-seeking behaviour, excessive concern with physical appearance, and inappropriate seductiveness. However, the key principle remains maintaining professional boundaries while ensuring the patient receives appropriate medical care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly addressing the inappropriate behaviour\u003C/strong\u003E and establishing clear boundaries is the most appropriate first step. This involves calmly but firmly explaining that the behaviour is inappropriate and makes you uncomfortable, while maintaining a professional therapeutic relationship. This approach allows for continued care while setting clear expectations for future interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgnoring the behaviour\u003C/strong\u003E may reinforce it and could lead to escalation of boundary violations. This is particularly problematic in histrionic personality disorder where attention-seeking behaviour is a core feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediately terminating the consultation\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly harsh response that could be harmful to the therapeutic relationship and potentially leave medical issues unaddressed. This would only be appropriate if the patient\u0027s behaviour was severely disruptive or threatening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransferring care without discussion\u003C/strong\u003E fails to address the underlying behaviour and may lead to the same pattern being repeated with other healthcare providers. It also denies the patient the opportunity to modify their behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScheduling more frequent follow-up appointments\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it could reinforce the attention-seeking behaviour that is characteristic of histrionic personality disorder and potentially escalate the boundary violations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDocumentation of such interactions is essential, including the specific behaviours observed and any actions taken. If the behaviour continues despite clear boundary setting, referral to another clinician may become necessary, but this should be discussed openly with the patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Professional boundaries must be maintained when patients with histrionic personality disorder display inappropriate seductive behaviour.","Clear, direct communication and documentation of boundary violations is essential.","Referral to another clinician may be necessary if therapeutic relationship is compromised."],"references":["Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52561"}},"question":{"data":{"